{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180912182337|859240022","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Don_Bacon_(politician)","to":"Don Bacon (politician)"}],"pages":{"46225952":{"pageid":46225952,"ns":0,"title":"Don Bacon (politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-20T19:45:08Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Don Bacon\n|image        = Donald Bacon Official House Photo.jpg\n|state        = [[Nebraska]]\n|district     = {{ushr|NE|2|2nd}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2017\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Brad Ashford]]\n|successor    = \n|birth_name   = Donald John Bacon\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1963|8|16}}\n|birth_place  = [[Momence, Illinois]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education    = [[Northern Illinois University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Phoenix]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])<br>[[National Defense University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n|spouse       = Angie Bacon\n|children     = 4 \n|website      = {{url|bacon.house.gov|House website}}\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Air Force}}\n|serviceyears = 1985\u20132014\n|rank         = [[File:US-O7 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]\n}}\n'''Donald John Bacon''' (born August 16, 1963) is a retired [[United States Air Force]] [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] and current [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Nebraska's 2nd congressional district]].\n\n==Education and military career==\nBacon is a native of [[Illinois]] and grew up on a family farm that grew corn, soybeans, and hay.<ref>del Guidice, Rachel; A General Joins the House\u2019s Conservative Ranks as New Congress Convenes; The Daily Signal; January 5, 2017; https://www.dailysignal.com/2017/01/05/a-general-joins-the-houses-conservative-ranks-as-new-congress-convenes/</ref><ref name=omaha/>\n\nHe attended [[Northern Illinois University]] and then gained his commission through the [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps]]. He specialized in [[electronic warfare]], intelligence, reconnaissance, and public affairs, and served as a Wing Commander at [[Ramstein Air Base]] in Germany and at [[Offutt Air Force Base]] in Nebraska, as a Group commander in Arizona, a Squadron commander in Arizona, and an Expeditionary Squadron commander in [[Iraq]].<ref>Don Bacon; Military Times; http://caucus.militarytimes.com/speaker/don-bacon/#.Wr6kR5PwbOQ</ref> Bacon has earned masters degrees from the [[University of Phoenix]] and the [[National War College]] of the [[National Defense University]]. His final assignment was as Director of ISR Strategy, Plans, Doctrine and Force Development, AF/A2, Headquarters U.S. Air Force at the Pentagon from July 2012 to 2014.<ref name=\"BaconAFBio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.af.mil/AboutUs/Biographies/Display/tabid/225/Article/108659/brigadier-general-donald-j-bacon.aspx|title=Brigadier General Donald J. Bacon|work=United States Air Force}}</ref> He picked up the nickname \"Bits\"\u2014a reference to his last name.<ref name=omaha/>\n\nIn 2015, at the age of 50, Bacon retired from the Air Force.<ref name=\"retire\">{{cite web|url=http://www.daily-journal.com/news/local/gen-bacon-set-to-retire/article_a1f0bc3d-c6ec-5e1b-8424-cd0ba43d6b91.html|title=Gen. Bacon set to retire|work=The Daily Journal|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref> During his 29.5 years in the Air Force, he was awarded the Distinguished Service Medal, two Legion of Merits, and two Bronze Stars, and was selected as Europe's top Air Force Wing Commander in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://donjbacon.com/about/|title=Biography|work=Biography|accessdate=September 21, 2017}}</ref> He served as an aide to [[U.S. House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Jeff Fortenberry]] and as an assistant professor at [[Bellevue University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.omaha.com/news/politics/don-bacon-is-a-fresh-face-in-politics-but-hardly/article_f78b4e23-4707-5de9-abc8-1bb5208abf61.html|title=Don Bacon is a \u2018fresh face\u2019 in politics but hardly a political neophyte|author=Robynn Tysver / World-Herald staff|work=omaha.com|accessdate=January 7, 2017}}</ref> \n[[Image:Donald J. Bacon.JPG|thumb|230 px|left|Bacon during his time in the U.S. Air Force.]]\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\nBacon ran for Congress in 2016 on four major issues: \u201caddressing harmful regulations by federal agencies such as the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Labor, reforming the tax code, addressing the national debt of nearly $20 trillion, and strengthening the military.\u201d<ref>de Guidice, Rachel; A General Joins the House\u2019s Conservative Ranks as New Congress Convenes; The Daily Signal; January 5, 2017; https://www.dailysignal.com/2017/01/05/a-general-joins-the-houses-conservative-ranks-as-new-congress-convenes/</ref>\n\nBacon won the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] [[primary election]] for the U.S. House of Representatives in {{ushr|NE|2}} in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Nebraska, 2016|2016 elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fremonttribune.com/news/local/retired-general-bids-for-ashford-house-seat/article_1d3f71e0-c206-5d2c-b519-4d6fbdf2c327.html|title=Retired general bids for Ashford House seat|author=Don Walton/Lincoln Journal Star|work=Fremont Tribune|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe general election race was characterized as a tossup, with Democratic incumbent [[Brad Ashford]] being seen as having the edge.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Loizzo | first1=Mike | title=Nebraska\u2019s 2nd Congressional District Race Remains a Toss-Up | url=http://nebraskaradionetwork.com/2016/09/26/nebraskas-2nd-congressional-district-race-remains-a-toss-up/ | date=September 26, 2016 | publisher=Nebraska Radio Network | accessdate=December 25, 2016}}</ref> Bacon faced and defeated Ashford in the general election on November 8, 2016.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Williams | first1=Jack | title=Bacon ousts Ashford in Second Congressional District | url=http://netnebraska.org/article/news/1049343/bacon-ousts-ashford-second-congressional-district | date=November 9, 2016 | publisher=''netnebraska.org'' | accessdate=December 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Bacon wins Nebraska House Seat After Ashford Concedes | url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/11/don-bacon-beats-brad-ashford-231105 | date=November 9, 2016 | publisher=[[Politico]] | accessdate=December 25, 2016}}</ref> After the release in October 2016 of a 2005 videotape showing Donald Trump making lewd remarks to Billy Bush, Bacon said that [[Donald Trump|Trump]] could not win the presidency and should withdraw from the race in favor of \u201ca strong conservative candidate, like [[Mike Pence]].\u201d Bacon did not say, however, that he would not vote for Trump since he did not believe \u201c[[Hillary Clinton|Hillary]] is the right person. I'm in a quandary.\u201d<ref>Tysver, Robynn; Don Bacon says Trump should step down, but he won't rule out voting for him; Omaha World Herald; October 8, 2016; http://www.omaha.com/news/politics/don-bacon-says-trump-should-step-down-but-he-won/article_a310cc52-8da8-11e6-b23e-f75a3224383d.html</ref>\n\nBacon received 49.4% of the vote to Ashford's 47.3%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nebraska U.S. House 2nd District Results: Don Bacon Wins|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/nebraska-house-district-2-ashford-bacon|accessdate=15 November 2016|publisher=The New York Times|date=November 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Official Report of the Board of State Canvassers|url=http://www.sos.ne.gov/elec/2016/pdf/2016-canvass-book.pdf|publisher= Nebraska Secretary of State|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref> He is the only Republican who defeated an incumbent Democrat in the 2016 House elections.\n\n===Tenure===\nBacon was assigned to the [[House Agriculture Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.omaha.com/news/politics/don-bacon-who-represents-the-mostly-urban-and-suburban-nd/article_07e4fe3c-816f-5091-a3ff-75865b3a714a.html|title=Don Bacon, who represents the mostly urban and suburban 2nd District, gets seat on House Agriculture Committee|first=Joseph |last=Morton|work=Omaha World-Herald|date=January 11, 2017|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref> He also sits on the [[House Committee on Homeland Security]] and [[House Armed Services Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/committee_info/oal.aspx|title=Official Committee Assignments, 115th Congress|work=Office of the Clerk, US House of Representatives|accessdate=September 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the [[Republican Main Street Partnership]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref> the bipartisan [[Climate Solutions Caucus]],<ref name=\"citizensclimatelobby.org\">{{cite web|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus-expands-to-24/|title=Climate Solutions Caucus expands to 24|accessdate= September 21, 2017}}</ref> the [[House Baltic Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://housebalticcaucus.webs.com/members|format=|publisher=House Baltic Caucus|date=|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref> and the [[Congressional Western Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref> \n\nAs of January 2018, Bacon had voted with his party in 95.7% of votes so far in the current session of Congress and voted in line with President Trump's position in 96.6% of votes.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/don-bacon/|title=Tracking Don Bacon In The Age Of Trump|last=Bycoffe|first=Aaron|date=2017-09-14|work=FiveThirtyEight|access-date=2017-09-14|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://projects.propublica.org/represent/members/B001298-don-bacon|title=Represent|last=Willis|first=Derek|work=ProPublica|access-date=2017-09-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n===Vote Smart Political Courage Test===\n[[Project Vote Smart|Vote Smart]], a non-profit, non-partisan research organization that collects and distributes information on candidates for public office in the United States, \"researched presidential and congressional candidates' public records to determine candidates' likely responses on certain key issues.\" According to Vote Smart's 2018 analysis, Bacon generally supports pro-life legislation, opposes an income tax increase, opposes decreasing defense spending, opposes federal spending and supports lowering taxes as means of promoting economic growth, opposes requiring states to adopt federal education standards, opposes the federal regulation of greenhouse gas emissions and government funding for renewable energy, opposes gun-control legislation, supports repealing the [[Affordable Care Act]], opposes same-sex marriage, supports the construction of a wall along the Mexican border and requiring immigrants who are unlawfully present to return to their country of origin before they are eligible for citizenship, and says the following about using military force to prevent governments hostile to the U.S. from possessing a nuclear weapon and increasing American intervetion in Middle Eastern conflicts beyond air support: ''\"As a retired brigadier general with almost 30 years of service, my views on these questions cannot be boiled down to a yes or no answer. Many things must be considered before using military force or sending Americans into combat. I don't know a single military leader who actually wants war, including myself. We must work to ensure our enemies do not have the ability to attack the United States with a nuclear weapon. We must promote peace through strength.\"''<ref>{{cite web|title=Don Bacon's Issue Positions (Political Courage Test)|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/166299/donald-bacon/#.W2CHXdJKhPY|publisher=[[Vote Smart]]|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nRegarding [[climate change]], Bacon has said: \"I don't think we know for certain how much of climate change is being caused by normal cyclical changes in weather vs. human causes. I support legislation that allows for continued incremental improvement in our environment, but oppose extreme measures that create significant economic and job disruption.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/bmedzw/nebraskas-climate-change-deniers|title=Nebraska's Climate Change Deniers|last=Byrne|first=Michael|date=25 April 2017|work=Vice|access-date=3 March 2018}}</ref> Bacon is a member of the bipartisan [[Climate Solutions Caucus]].<ref name=\"citizensclimatelobby.org\"/> In an [[American Family Association]] questionnaire from 2016, Bacon disagreed with the statement that \"Governments should pay to develop wind and solar energy solutions until they are economically feasible.\" In the same survey, he supported \"deregulating domestic oil exploration and drilling.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Don_Bacon_Energy_+_Oil.htm|title=Don Bacon on Energy & Oil|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=2017-04-01}}</ref><div></div>\n\n===Immigration===\nIn August 2017, Bacon and five of his House colleagues urged President Trump to allow [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|DACA]] youths, also known as \"Dreamers,\" to remain in the United States until some permanent solution could be arranged. \"Children brought to the United States at a young age did not have a choice in the matter,\" the Congress members wrote the President. \"They did not willingly seek to violate American statutes when they traveled with their families across our borders, as the alternative was often life without primary caregivers.\" He has said that he would \"fight like heck so that people under DACA will never have to fear deportation again.\"<ref>Walton, Don; Rep. Don Bacon urges Trump to protect DACA youths; Lincoln Journal Star; August 25, 2017; http://journalstar.com/news/state-and-regional/federal-politics/rep-don-bacon-urges-trump-to-protect-daca-youths/article_9b68a039-1d3e-552c-babf-a26bbfa89590.html</ref><ref name=\"dailynebraskan.com\">Gilchrist, Logan; Don Bacon spoke at UNL seminar, students skeptical about his motivations; The Daily Nebraskan; October 19, 2017; http://www.dailynebraskan.com/news/don-bacon-spoke-at-unl-seminar-students-skeptical-about-his/article_844f0722-b47e-11e7-b14f-dfc83e8e78e7.html</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Bacon re-introduced the Kerrie Orozco Act, which would \"allow the spouses of first responders, killed in the line of duty, access to a quicker process of becoming an American citizen.\" He explained that it would \"honor one of the heroes of the Omaha Police Department and help the surviving spouse, child, or parent of our brave first responders by allowing them to still get citizenship even after the death of first responder loved ones.\" The act was named for a first responder who died while her husband, Hector, was waiting for his green card.<ref>Don Bacon to re-introduce Kerrie Orozco Act; 3NewsNow; April 5, 2017; https://www.3newsnow.com/news/local-news/don-bacon-to-re-introduce-kerri-orozco-act-friday</ref>\n\n===Military===\nAt a Brookings Institution event in October 2017, Bacon discussed the importance of military readiness, noting that at the beginning of his career U.S. Air Force crews had flown two hours to every one flown by [[Russia]] or [[China]], but were now flying about one-third as many hours as they had then. \"When you fly one-third of the hours, people get out because it's not rewarding,\" said Bacon. He also said that the \"gravest threat\" to military preparedness was the \"partisan divide\" in government, which had prevented necessary increases in spending.<ref>Livingston, Ian; Reps. Don Bacon and Rick Larsen share their views on defense priorities and challenges; Brookings; October 24, 2017; https://www.brookings.edu/blog/order-from-chaos/2017/10/24/reps-don-bacon-and-rick-larsen-share-their-views-on-defense-priorities-and-challenges/</ref>\n\nIn addition, he pointed to the Russian threat, underscoring the need to respond to the challenge posed by both Russia and China in [[outer space]] as well as in [[cyberspace]]. Bacon considers a partnership with China possible despite its regional power ambitions, but says \"Russia is an adversary\" that is \"working against our goals.\" He finds Russia's activity in [[Ukraine]] and the [[Balkans]] disturbing and believes in a stronger U.S. military presence in the latter region.<ref name=\"dailynebraskan.com\"/>\n\nIn November 2017, Bacon told an [[Electronic Warfare]] (EW) conference that the U.S. military needed \"to elevate the electromagnetic spectrum to an official domain of warfare - alongside land, sea, air, space, and cyberspace - and appoint general officers as EW advocates in all four services and to the joint staff.\" He said that when he was \"a young EWO (Electronic Warfare Officer), there was no doubt we had the best electronic warfare capabilities in the world,\" but that after the fall of the USSR \"we let it atrophy for a decade-and-a-half.\" It was now time, he said, to push the effort on this front \"into high gear.\" He has been described as \"probably the most qualified congressman\" on the subject of EW.<ref>Freedberg Jr, Sydney J; Spectrum (EW) Should Be A Warfighting Domain: Rep. Bacon; Breaking Defense; November 29, 2017; https://breakingdefense.com/2017/11/spectrum-ew-should-be-a-warfighting-domain-rep-bacon/</ref>\n\n===Terrorism===\nBacon has said that Barack Obama's administration has \u201cunderestimated\u201d [[ISIS]]. \u201cI hope we can be able to work with more of our traditional allies to go after ISIS.\u201d<ref>del Guidice, Rachel; A General Joins the House\u2019s Conservative Ranks as New Congress Convenes; The Daily Signal; January 5, 2017;https://www.dailysignal.com/2017/01/05/a-general-joins-the-houses-conservative-ranks-as-new-congress-convenes/</ref>\n\n===Health care===\nBacon opposes abortion after the twentieth week of pregnancy.<ref>Bess, Gabby; An Incredibly Upsetting List of All the New Republican Congress Members; VICE; January 6, 2017; https://broadly.vice.com/en_us/article/qvd84q/an-incredibly-upsetting-list-of-all-the-new-republican-congress-members</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Tysver|first1=Robynn|title=Don Bacon is a \u2018fresh face\u2019 in politics but hardly a political neophyte|url=http://www.omaha.com/news/politics/don-bacon-is-a-fresh-face-in-politics-but-hardly/article_f78b4e23-4707-5de9-abc8-1bb5208abf61.html|accessdate=10 January 2018|publisher=Omaha World Herald|date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> He says that care currently being provided at [[Planned Parenthood]] could be better delivered through community health care centers that do not also provide abortion services.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morton|first1=Joseph|title=Don Bacon denounces claims in Democrats\u2019 health care fliers, calls one attack ad 'very vile'|url=http://www.omaha.com/news/metro/don-bacon-denounces-claims-in-democrats-health-care-fliers-calls/article_283eaff8-c600-5966-800a-fb73b99ff918.html|accessdate=10 January 2018|publisher=Omaha World Herald|date=November 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBacon favors repealing the [[Affordable Care Act]], commonly known as Obamacare.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.omaha.com/livewellnebraska/affordable-care-act-repeal-on-fast-track-but-gop-replacement/article_8b47c7a3-cde7-5f95-b221-67a72ff8a68c.html|title=Affordable Care Act repeal on fast track, but GOP replacement not yet in sight|last=Bureau|first=Joseph Morton / World-Herald|work=Omaha.com|access-date=2017-04-01|language=en}}</ref> He was supportive of the March 2017 version of American Health Care Act, the GOP's replacement plan for Obamacare.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/03/20/us/politics/health-care-whip-count.html|title=How House Republicans Planned to Vote on the Obamacare Replacement|last=The New York Times|date=2017-03-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-01|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On May 4, 2017, Bacon voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] and pass the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]], nicknamed \"Trumpcare.\"<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/04/politics/house-health-care-vote/index.html|title=How every member voted on health care bill|last=Staff|first=C. N. N.|website=CNN|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\nHe is a steadfast backer of Israel, and supports the United States recognizing [[Jerusalem]] as Israel's capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewishinsider.com/12020/meet-kosher-bacon-congress/|title=Meet the 'Most Kosher Bacon' in Congress|last=Magid|first=Aaron|website=Jewish Insider|access-date=2017-09-21}}</ref> In an [[American Family Association]] candidate questionnaire from 2016, Bacon opposed the question \"The U.S. military should wait for militant Islamic groups to directly threaten our national security on our shores, rather than eradicate them now wherever they may be worldwide.\" He said the U.S. needs \"to defeat ISIS with assertive leadership, our superior airpower, and special forces.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Don_Bacon_War_+_Peace.htm|title=Don Bacon on War & Peace|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=2018-03-17}}</ref>\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\nHe opposes same-sex marriage.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Don_Bacon.htm|title=Don Bacon on the Issues|last=OnTheIssues.org|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=2017-04-01}}</ref> Bacon supports defining marriage as being between \"one man and one woman.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Don_Bacon_Civil_Rights.htm|title=Don Bacon on Civil Rights|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=2018-03-17}}</ref>\n\n===Drug policy===\nIn the [[American Family Association]] candidate questionnaire from 2016, Bacon disagreed that \"Marijuana should be legalized and regulated like tobacco and alcohol.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Don Bacon on Drugs|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Don_Bacon_Drugs.htm|publisher=[[On The Issues]]|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Internet===\nIn March 2017, Bacon voted to return jurisdiction over the internet to the [[Federal Trade Commission]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bacon.house.gov/media/press-releases/rep-bacon-votes-affirm-ftc-s-privacy-rules-process|title=Rep. Bacon votes to reaffirm FTC's Privacy Rules Process|website=House of Representatives Press Release|date=2017-03-29|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> by reversing an October 2016 rule that subjected online activity to control by the [[Federal Communications Commission]]. Bacon's vote was in line with the position of the business-oriented lobbying group the [[United States Chamber of Commerce]] on this rule.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uschamber.com/above-the-fold/here-are-the-facts-congress-did-not-give-away-your-internet-privacy|title=Here are the Facts. Congress Did Not Give Away Your Internet Privacy.|website=United States Chamber of Commerce|date=2017-03-31|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> Bacon opposed the continuation of [[net neutrality in the United States]] in support of FCC Chairman [[Ajit Pai]]'s repeal of Title II classification of ISPs. Bacon received $7,000 in campaign contributions from the telecommunications industry during the 2016 election cycle.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/29/15100620/congress-fcc-isp-web-browsing-privacy-fire-sale|title=The 265 members of Congress who sold you out to ISPs, and how much it cost to buy them|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBacon and his wife, Angie, have four children and live in [[Papillion, Nebraska]].<ref name=omaha>{{cite web|url=http://www.omaha.com/news/politics/citing-military-and-foreign-policy-as-priorities-retired-brig-gen/article_596b36ca-d24a-11e4-b85d-cbd740287a97.html|title=Citing military and foreign policy as priorities, retired Brig. Gen. Don Bacon announces bid for Congress|work=Omaha.com|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://bacon.house.gov/ Congressman Don Bacon] official US House website\n*[http://donjbacon.com Don Bacon for Congress]\n*{{DMOZ|Regional/North_America/United_States/Nebraska/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Don_Bacon_%5BR-2%5D|Don Bacon}}\n* {{C-SPAN|donaldjbacon}}\n*{{ CongLinks | congbio = B001298 | fec = H6NE02125 | votesmart = 166299 | congress = don-bacon/B001298}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n|  state = Nebraska\n|  district = 2\n|  before = [[Brad Ashford]]\n|  start = 2017}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jodey Arrington]]<br>R-[[Texas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=371st}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Banks]]<br>R-[[Indiana]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{NE-FedRep}}\n{{USCongRep-start\n| congresses= 115th [[United States Congress]]\n| state= [[United States congressional delegations from Nebraska|Nebraska]]}}\n{{USCongRep/NE/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Current members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{NebraskaUSRepresentatives}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bacon, Don}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Momence, Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Papillion, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:National War College alumni]]\n[[Category:Northern Illinois University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Phoenix alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force generals]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Nebraska Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]"}]}}}}